Final Report
Customer & Orders Data Analysis using SQL
Project Overview

This project analyzes customer and order data using SQL. The database contains two tables: customers and orders with 100+ records. The objective of this project is to understand customer purchasing behavior, product performance, and overall sales trends using SQL queries.

Dataset Information
Customers Table

Contains customer-related information:

customer_id
customer_name
city
gender
age
signup_date
Orders Table

Contains order-related information:

order_id
customer_id
order_date
product_name
category
amount
SQL Concepts Used
Aggregate Functions

Used:

SUM()
AVG()
COUNT()
MIN()
MAX()

Purpose:

Calculate revenue
Find average order value
Count customers and orders
Joins Used
INNER JOIN

Used to combine matching customer and order records.

LEFT JOIN

Used to find customers without orders.

RIGHT JOIN

Used to identify orders without customer details.

FULL OUTER JOIN

Used to display all customers and all orders together.

Window Functions Used
RANK()

Ranks customers based on total spending.

DENSE_RANK()

Provides ranking without gaps.

ROW_NUMBER()

Assigns unique row numbers to customer orders.

Running Total

Tracks cumulative sales over time.

UNION Operations

Used UNION and UNION ALL to:

Combine multiple result sets
Compare different product categories
Analyze customer groups and sales data
Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Performed analysis on:

Total revenue
Monthly sales
Category-wise sales
City-wise customer distribution
Top-selling products
Customer spending patterns
Key Insights
Electronics category generated the highest revenue.
Laptop and Mobile products were top-selling items.
Customers from Hyderabad, Chennai, and Bangalore placed more orders.
Repeat customers contributed significantly to total sales.
High-value orders increased overall business revenue.
